<br>
I am not originally from CA nor do I currently live there, but as a &quot;Yankee&quot; I think it gives me a pretty unique perspective on Californian Culture and the political shenanigans they tolerate there. First a little back story... I've lived in Pasadena (no need to expand on the political climate in the Los Angeles area) and I've also lived in Sacramento which is a bastion of &quot;compassionate conservatism&quot; to use a term from that farce we call the 2000 elections. <br>
<br>
I think the thing I noticed most about CA politics is that regardless of what side of the fence these people are on, they are almost to a man(woman) extraordinarily tolerant of corruption, &quot;poor behavior&quot; for lack of a better term, and just all around shadiness on the parts of their politicians. Living in CT, I can be honest about the fact that politicians in the northeast have probably the worst track record in the country when it comes to corruption, and generally Yankees are tolerant of it as long as the streets are safe, wages are up, etc etc etc, but the complacence here is _nothing_ compared to what (most) Californians will stand for. &quot;Oh, Davis got soft money in exchange for de-regulating and turning a blind eye to price gauging? That's nice. How does he feel about saving the gay baby whales?&quot; Is this an embellishment? Yes. Is it terribly far from the truth? Hardly. <br>
<br>
The perfect exemplification of this is the fact that Davis was re-elected last year. Friends all over the state suffered through friendly letters from PG&amp;E saying &quot;Every other Tuesday from 12 noon to 6pm, you get no electricity. Your bill for this month is $893.47.  Have a nice day and remember not to open the fridge.&quot; This went on for MONTHS and nobody was exempt from it except for the lucky few up north who were on the PacNW power grid. Its finally come out now that Davis pretty much allowed electricity price gauging, yet the people of California still re-elected him. Why? Because he's soft on special interest groups, and in a country where only about 40% of the eligible population turns out to vote, special interest groups are the only ones that matter. My fiercest encouragement and heartiest wishes go out to those in CA making an effort to recall the vote. <p>Svarien Deschain<br>
